The Nigeria Customs Joint Border Drill Operations covering North Central states has within the last 40 days generated a total Duty Paid Value of N1, 207, 223, 380.00. It also arrested 53 suspects during the period under review and intercepted a tipper lorry with registration number ZAR 803 XA that carefully concealed 140 bags of 50kg foreign rice in sharp sand. The coordinator, Joint Border Drill Operations in the zone, Mohammed Uba Garba made these disclosures in Ilorin, Kwara State yesterday. “For the period of 40 days under review, a total Duty Paid Value of N1, 207, 223, 380.00 was generated and 53 suspects arrested,” Garba stated. He further disclosed that some die-hard smugglers have  resorted to using tricycles (Keke Napep) and commercial motorcycles to smuggle rice into the country. He added that the joint operation raided two warehouses at Abayawo and Ita- Merin areas, in Ilorin metropolis, suspected to stockpile foreign par boiled rice. Garba said that the two stores were raided and a total of 450 and 224 bags of foreign parboiled rice of 50kg each, respectively, were discovered to have been smuggled into the state. “It will be recalled that late last month, the patrol team covering Babanna axis of the Sector in Niger State, intercepted two Mitsubishi Canter with Reg. No XA-241-WEL and XC-166-SUL, respectively laden with 54 drums of smuggled petrol with a duty paid Value (DPV) 1.9 million with two suspects. “I want you to send this gospel to the enemies of Nigerian economy that this sector has stepped up extra measures to combat the influx of foreign rice smuggling and other prohibited items in to the country,” he said. 